 Gardasil's benefit for men and women alike. This book demonstrates why in the ten years since Gardasil's U.S. launch its low rates of public acceptance have their origins in the early days of the vaccine dissemination. Not Quite a Cancer Vaccine addresses the on-going expansion in U.S. healthcare of patients-as-consumers and the ubiquitous, and sometimes insidious, health marketing of large pharma.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCervix uterixCancerxPrevention. 0aPapillomavirus vaccines. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / General.2bisacsh  aBig Pharma.  aHPV.  aanthropology.  acancer.  acervical cancer.  agardasil.  ahealth policy.  ahealthcare.  amedical anthropology.  apediactric.  apharma.  apharmaceuticals.  apublic health.  aus healthcare.  avaccine.1 aGottlieb, Samantha D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813587806zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813587806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813587806.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK